Solid ClF$_{3}$ is known to exist in several structures (Villars, 2018): \begin{itemize} \item From -83$^{\circ}$C to the melting point it takes on the current structure. \item Between -109 and -100$^{\circ}$C it takes on an \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3_oP16_62_c_cd-005}{orthorhombic structure with 4 formula units in the primitive cell}. \item Below -109$^{\circ}$C there is another structure for which we have no data. \item (Villars, 2018) give no data on the structure between -100 and -83$^{\circ}$C. \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 \href{https://scibabe.com/daily-mos-the-unharnessed-chlorine-trifluoride/}{ClF$_{3}$ is extremely dangerous} in any of these forms. 
 \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3_mP32_14_2e_6e-001}{Monoclinic ClFe$_{3}$} and \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3_mP32_14_2e_6e-002}{CrTe$_{3}$} have the same AFLOW prototype label, AB3\_mP32\_14\_2e\_6e. This label is similar to that of \href{current_web_home_dir/A3B_mP32_14_6e_2e-001}{$\gamma$-WO$_{3}$}, A3B\_mP32\_14\_6e\_2e. The unique structures are generated by the same symmetry operations with different sets of parameters ({\tt --params}) specified in their corresponding CIF files.
